(42, 10, 19, 42, 21, 17, 18, 'nothing shall by any means hurt you', 'Protection Amid Persecution', 'Both passages emphasize divine protection for believers. In Luke 10:19, the assurance of power over harm parallels the promise in Luke 21:17-18 that no harm will come to them despite hatred.', 'theme', 0.9649999999999999, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 19, 26, 2, 6, 6, 'scorpions', 'Fearlessness in Adversity', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of fearlessness in the face of danger. Luke speaks of power over ''serpents and scorpions,'' while Ezekiel encourages not to fear ''scorpions'' among a rebellious people.', 'theme', 0.923, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 20, 66, 20, 15, 15, 'your names are written in heaven', 'Connection of Names Written', 'Both passages emphasize the significance of names being written, with Luke highlighting the joy of having one''s name in heaven and Revelation warning of the consequences for those not found in the book of life. This connection highlights the importance of one''s standing in relation to divine records.', 'theme', 0.46099999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 20, 40, 7, 22, 23, 'your names are written in heaven', 'Rejoicing in True Faith', 'This connection highlights the distinction between external works and true relationship with God. Both passages emphasize the importance of being known by Christ rather than merely performing acts in His name.', 'theme', 0.45399999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 20, 58, 12, 23, 23, 'your names are written in heaven', 'Names Written in Heaven', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of names being ''written in heaven,'' highlighting the assurance of belonging to God''s kingdom. This connection underscores the spiritual significance of one''s identity in relation to divine recognition.', 'theme', 0.43299999999999994, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 20, 66, 21, 27, 27, 'your names are written in heaven', 'Names Written in Heaven', 'Both passages emphasize the significance of being ''written'' in a divine record. Luke 10:20 highlights the joy of having names written in heaven, while Revelation 21:27 refers to those written in the Lamb''s book of life, suggesting a shared theme of divine recognition and assurance of salvation.', 'theme', 0.43299999999999994, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 20, 27, 12, 1, 1, 'your names are written in heaven', 'Names Written in Heaven', 'This connection highlights the theme of names being recorded, as both passages refer to those whose names are ''written'' in a significant book. Luke emphasizes rejoicing in having one''s name written in heaven, while Daniel speaks of deliverance for those found written in the book during a time of trouble.', 'theme', 0.419, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 20, 2, 32, 32, 32, 'your names are written in heaven', 'Connection of Names in Heaven', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of names being recorded in a divine book. Luke 10:20 speaks of names written in heaven, while Exodus 32:32 refers to a book that contains names, highlighting the significance of divine acknowledgment.', 'theme', 0.412, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 20, 26, 13, 9, 9, 'written in heaven', 'Names Written in Heaven', 'This connection highlights the theme of being ''written'' in a divine record. Luke emphasizes rejoicing in having names written in heaven, while Ezekiel warns that false prophets will not be written in the assembly of God''s people.', 'theme', 0.40499999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 21, 47, 4, 3, 3, 'hid these things from the wise', 'Revelation to the Lost', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of revelation being hidden from certain groups. In Luke, it is revealed to ''babes,'' while in 2 Corinthians, the gospel is ''hid'' from ''them that are lost.'' This connection highlights the contrast between those who receive understanding and those who do not.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 21, 40, 11, 25, 27, 'thou hast hid these things from the wise and prudent, and hast revealed them unto babes', 'Connection of Revelation to the Humble', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of God revealing truths to the humble while concealing them from the wise. The identical phrasing in both texts underscores this connection, highlighting a consistent message about divine revelation.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 21, 40, 13, 11, 16, NULL, 'Revelation to the Simple', 'Both passages emphasize the idea that understanding the mysteries of the kingdom is revealed to the humble and hidden from the wise. This connection highlights the contrast between those who perceive and those who do not, as seen in the phrase ''hath hid these things from the wise.''', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 21, 46, 2, 6, 8, 'hast revealed them unto babes', 'Hidden Wisdom and Revelation', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of hidden wisdom revealed to the humble. Luke highlights God''s choice to reveal truths to ''babes,'' while 1 Corinthians speaks of ''hidden wisdom'' not known by worldly powers.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 21, 49, 1, 5, 5, 'for so it seemed good in thy sight', 'Divine Revelation and Adoption', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine revelation and the concept of being children of God. Both passages emphasize the good pleasure of the Father in revealing truth and adopting believers.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 21, 60, 2, 1, 2, 'even so, Father; for so it seemed good in thy sight', 'Connection of Spiritual Growth', 'This connection highlights the theme of spiritual growth through humility. Both passages emphasize the idea of ''babes'' receiving revelation and desiring the ''sincere milk'' of the word, suggesting a link between childlike faith and spiritual nourishment.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 21, 18, 5, 12, 14, 'wise and prudent', 'Wisdom and Revelation Contrast', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of God confounding the wise and revealing truth to the humble. In Luke, Jesus thanks the Father for hiding truths from the ''wise and prudent,'' while Job speaks of God disappointing the ''devices of the crafty.'' This connection highlights the divine reversal of expectations regarding wisdom.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 22, 40, 11, 27, 27, NULL, 'Connection of Divine Revelation', 'Both passages emphasize the exclusive knowledge of the Father and the Son. They highlight that only the Son can reveal the Father to others, indicating a deep relational understanding between them.', 'theme', 0.426, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 22, 43, 1, 18, 18, 'he to whom the Son will reveal him', 'Revelation of the Father', 'Both passages emphasize the unique relationship between the Father and the Son. Luke highlights that the Son reveals the Father, while John states that the Son declares Him.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 22, 43, 6, 44, 46, 'who the Father is, but the Son', 'Connection of Divine Revelation', 'Both passages emphasize the relationship between the Father and the Son in revealing truth. Luke 10:22 states that only the Son can reveal the Father, while John 6:44-46 highlights that no one can come to the Son unless drawn by the Father, indicating a divine teaching process.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 22, 47, 4, 6, 6, 'who the Father is, but the Son', 'Knowledge of God through Christ', 'This connection highlights the theme of revelation, as both passages emphasize the knowledge of God being revealed through Jesus Christ. Luke 10:22 speaks of the Son revealing the Father, while 2 Corinthians 4:6 describes the light of knowledge shining in our hearts through Christ.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
